German-Americans have played a significant role in the history and development of the United States since the 17th century. They are one of the largest ancestry groups in the country, with over 43 million Americans of German heritage. German-Americans have made numerous contributions to American society and culture, from iconic structures like the Brooklyn Bridge to inventions like airplanes and jeans. They have also excelled in various professions, including first responders, public servants, scientists, entrepreneurs, farmers, authors, and athletes. The strong ties between the United States and Germany are emphasized, with a commitment to shared democratic values and cooperation. German-American Day is celebrated to honor the heritage and contributions of German-Americans, urging all Americans to recognize their history and contributions.